Coal miners in Siberia ended their strike today after exacting promises of better food, housing and working conditions, but the wave of unrest they launched continued in other key coal regions. The coal industry employs more than 1 million workers. Until Gorbachev rose to power in 1985, strikes were not tolerated. Despite announcements that President Mikhail S. The labor unrest is the Soviet Union's worst in six decades. The Coal Mining Ministry will continue to run the mines, but the miners will have a much greater say setting production levels and allocating the profits, he said. 